<br>
But what makes telemarketers (as a class now, I'm sure there are some sainted individuals who sell on the phone for a living and have to bear the taint of their class) SCUM OF THE EARTH is the blatant lying which many of them employ routinely to do their job.<br>
<br>
My secretary is always taking calls from telemarketers claiming to be personal friends of mine. Or, if they're trying to get me to switch our phone service from Verizon (the big provider in our area, and the one we use) they lie and tell her they're &quot;calling from Verizon.&quot; Then when I get on (I do enjoy taking telemarketing calls to mess with them, LOL, when I'm not on EQ boards) and they start their &quot;switch pitch&quot;, I always ask them &quot;Hmm... didn't you say you're calling FROM Verizon? Why would you want me to LEAVE Verizon?&quot; They always have the pre-programmed excuse that &quot;we're working WITH Verizon in this area to provide phone services&quot; which means, once translated, that they're a secondary parasite provider spawned by phone deregulation, trying to switch Verizon users through misleading representations.<br>
<br>
Hey, I don't particularly like Verizon but am I going to switch all my phone service to an outfit which starts out their pitch with LIES?<br>
<br>
Thing is, these companies are not always &quot;fly-by-night&quot; outfits. And I think the pitch their reps use is part of corporate training. Which reinforces my conclusion that TELEMARKETERS ARE, AS A CLASS, THE SCUM OF THE EARTH.<br>
<br>
